# After

The navigation drawer animation switches to composite-only properties (`transform` + `opacity`), uses `ease-out` easing, a 250ms duration, and respects `prefers-reduced-motion`.

```css
/* Nav drawer — animate only composite properties (transform, opacity) */
.nav-drawer {
  /* Position off-screen using transform — not width/height */
  transform: translateX(-280px);
  opacity: 0;
  width: 280px;         /* fixed dimensions, never animated */
  height: 100vh;
  overflow: hidden;
  background-color: #1a1a2e;
  /* ease-out: fast start → gentle stop — natural for entering elements (Ch 1) */
  transition:
    transform 250ms ease-out,
    opacity   200ms ease-out;
  /* Hint the browser to promote this element to its own compositor layer */
  will-change: transform;
}

.nav-drawer.open {
  transform: translateX(0);
  opacity: 1;
}

/* Menu items stagger in using animation-delay for follow-through (Ch 1) */
.nav-drawer .menu-item {
  opacity: 0;
  transform: translateX(-12px);
  transition:
    opacity   180ms ease-out,
    transform 180ms ease-out;
}

.nav-drawer.open .menu-item {
  opacity: 1;
  transform: translateX(0);
}

/* Stagger each item for natural overlapping action */
.nav-drawer.open .menu-item:nth-child(1) { transition-delay: 60ms; }
.nav-drawer.open .menu-item:nth-child(2) { transition-delay: 90ms; }
.nav-drawer.open .menu-item:nth-child(3) { transition-delay: 120ms; }
.nav-drawer.open .menu-item:nth-child(4) { transition-delay: 150ms; }

/* Accessibility: remove all motion for users who prefer it (Ch 5) */
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  .nav-drawer,
  .nav-drawer .menu-item {
    transition: opacity 150ms linear !important;
    transform: none !important;
  }
}
```

Key improvements:
- `transform: translateX()` replaces `width`/`height` animation — `transform` and `opacity` are the only composite-only properties that animate on the GPU without triggering layout recalculation (Ch 3: Performance — composite-only properties)
- Duration reduced from 1.5s to 250ms — functional UI animations should be 200–500ms; 1.5s feels sluggish and blocks the user (Ch 1: Timing and duration)
- `ease-out` replaces `linear` — entering elements should start fast and slow to a stop; linear easing feels robotic for UI elements (Ch 1: 12 Principles — ease in / ease out)
- `will-change: transform` promotes the drawer to its own compositor layer, enabling smooth 60fps animation on mobile devices (Ch 3: will-change)
- Staggered `transition-delay` on menu items creates overlapping action — the drawer and its children don't all stop simultaneously, producing a more natural feel (Ch 1: 12 Principles — follow-through and overlapping action)
- `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)` is implemented — users with vestibular disorders receive a simple fade instead of a lateral sweep (Ch 5: Accessibility — prefers-reduced-motion)

# Before

A CSS animation on a navigation drawer that animates `width` and `height` (layout-triggering properties) with `linear` easing and a 1.5-second duration, with no `prefers-reduced-motion` support.

```css
.nav-drawer {
  width: 0;
  height: 0;
  overflow: hidden;
  background-color: #1a1a2e;
}

.nav-drawer.open {
  width: 280px;
  height: 100vh;
  /* Animates layout properties — forces browser to recalculate layout
     on every frame, causing jank on low-powered devices */
  transition: width 1.5s linear, height 1.5s linear;
}

.nav-drawer .menu-item {
  opacity: 0;
  /* Also animates layout property margin */
  margin-left: -280px;
  transition: opacity 1.5s linear, margin-left 1.5s linear;
}

.nav-drawer.open .menu-item {
  opacity: 1;
  margin-left: 0;
}

/* No prefers-reduced-motion support — users with vestibular
   disorders experience the full 1.5s sweep animation */
```

# After

The discount calculation is split into single-responsibility methods with intention-revealing names, guard clauses replacing nesting, and constants replacing magic numbers.

```java
private static final double PREMIUM_DISCOUNT = 0.85;
private static final double MEMBER_DISCOUNT  = 0.90;
private static final double SHIPPING_CREDIT  = 5.99;
private static final double FREE_SHIPPING_THRESHOLD = 100.00;

public double calculateOrderTotal(Order order, CustomerTier tier, boolean freeShippingPromo) {
    if (order == null || order.getItems() == null) {
        return 0;
    }
    return order.getItems().stream()
            .filter(item -> item.getQty() > 0)
            .mapToDouble(item -> calculateLineTotal(item, tier, freeShippingPromo))
            .sum();
}

private double calculateLineTotal(Item item, CustomerTier tier, boolean freeShippingPromo) {
    double subtotal = item.getPrice() * item.getQty();
    double discounted = applyTierDiscount(subtotal, tier);
    return applyShippingCredit(discounted, freeShippingPromo);
}

private double applyTierDiscount(double subtotal, CustomerTier tier) {
    return switch (tier) {
        case PREMIUM -> subtotal * PREMIUM_DISCOUNT;
        case MEMBER  -> subtotal * MEMBER_DISCOUNT;
        default      -> subtotal;
    };
}

private double applyShippingCredit(double amount, boolean freeShippingPromo) {
    if (!freeShippingPromo || amount <= FREE_SHIPPING_THRESHOLD) {
        return amount;
    }
    return amount - SHIPPING_CREDIT;
}
```

Key improvements:
- Descriptive name `calculateOrderTotal` states exactly what the method does (G20: Function Names Should Say What They Do)
- Guard clause at the top of the public method eliminates two levels of nesting (G28: Encapsulate Conditionals)
- Each private method does exactly one thing: calculate, discount, or apply credit (G30: Functions Should Do One Thing)
- Magic numbers `0.85`, `0.90`, `5.99`, `100` extracted to named constants (G25: Replace Magic Numbers with Named Constants)
- `String` tier replaced with `CustomerTier` enum, enabling exhaustive `switch` (J3: Constants versus Enums)

# Before

A Java method that handles order discount calculation with poor naming, deep nesting, and multiple responsibilities mixed together.

```java
public double calc(Order o, String t, boolean f) {
    double r = 0;
    if (o != null) {
        if (o.getItems() != null && o.getItems().size() > 0) {
            for (Item i : o.getItems()) {
                if (i.getQty() > 0) {
                    double p = i.getPrice() * i.getQty();
                    if (t.equals("PREMIUM")) {
                        p = p * 0.85;
                    } else if (t.equals("MEMBER")) {
                        p = p * 0.90;
                    } else {
                        p = p * 1.0;
                    }
                    if (f) {
                        // free shipping promo
                        if (p > 100) {
                            p = p - 5.99;
                        }
                    }
                    r = r + p;
                }
            }
        }
    }
    return r;
}
```

# Clean Code Review: `FileProcessor`

## Quick Summary

`FileProcessor` is a Java class that validates, reads, parses, and persists a file-backed record. The logic is straightforward, but the class uses a C-style integer error-code protocol for control flow instead of exceptions, which is the primary source of its readability and maintainability problems. Several secondary naming and structural issues compound the pain.

---

## What's Good

- **Guard clauses and early returns** are already in use. The function avoids deep nesting by returning immediately on failure — that instinct is right; the mechanism just needs upgrading.
- **`processFile` is reasonably linear.** Reading top-to-bottom, the happy path is easy to follow: check → read → parse → save. The stepdown structure (Ch. 3) is present even if imperfect.
- **Helper methods are extracted.** `readFile` and `parseRecord` (implied) are separate, which is the right decomposition direction.

---

## Issues

### 🔴 Critical

**1. Error codes instead of exceptions — G4, G30, J3, Ch. 7**

The entire control-flow model is built on `int` return codes (`ERR_FILE_NOT_FOUND`, `ERR_PERMISSION`, etc.). Clean Code is unambiguous: *prefer exceptions to error codes*. Error codes force every caller to inspect the return value immediately or silently swallow failures. They pollute the calling code with conditional logic that has nothing to do with the caller's actual job, and they make it easy to forget to check at all.

The `int` constants should become a typed enum (J3: *Constants versus Enums*) at minimum, and the method should throw typed exceptions rather than returning sentinel values.

```java
// Before — caller must check an int
int result = processor.processFile(path);
if (result != FileProcessor.SUCCESS) { ... }

// After — caller uses standard Java control flow
try {
    processor.processFile(path);
} catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
    // handle
} catch (FileAccessException e) {
    // handle
}
```

---

**2. `readFile` silently swallows exceptions and returns `null` — Ch. 7 ("Don't return null"), G4**

```java
private String readFile(File f) {
    try {
        return new String(Files.readAllBytes(f.toPath()));
    } catch (Exception e) {
        return null;         // <-- all failure information is lost
    }
}
```

Catching `Exception` broadly and returning `null` destroys all diagnostic context. The caller can't tell whether the read failed due to an `IOException`, an `OutOfMemoryError`, or a `SecurityException`. Returning `null` then forces the caller (`processFile`) to null-check the result — pushing the error-handling burden up the chain without adding any information.

This is a double violation: catching too broadly (*G4: Overridden Safeties*) and returning null (*Ch. 7: Don't Return Null*). The method should either propagate the exception with context or wrap it in a domain exception.

```java
// After
private String readFile(File file) throws FileReadException {
    try {
        return Files.readString(file.toPath());
    } catch (IOException e) {
        throw new FileReadException("Failed to read file: " + file.getPath(), e);
    }
}
```

---

**3. Null check on `new File(path)` is dead code — G9**

```java
File f = new File(path);
if (f == null) return ERR_FILE_NOT_FOUND;
```

`new File(path)` never returns `null` in Java. If `path` is `null`, the constructor throws `NullPointerException` before the assignment completes. This check is unreachable (*G9: Dead Code*) and misleads readers into thinking `File` construction can fail silently. Delete it.

---

### 🟡 Improvement

**4. Single-letter variable name `f` — N1, N5**

```java
File f = new File(path);
```

`f` carries no meaning. The variable lives for the duration of a multi-step method and is referenced four times. *N5: Use Long Names for Long Scopes* — `f` is acceptable in a 2-line loop, not as a class-level collaborator. Rename to `file`.

---

**5. `FileProcessor` is a vague class name — N1, N4**

`Processor` is explicitly called out in Clean Code as one of the vague manager/processor/handler names to avoid. What does this class process? What is its single responsibility? The class reads, parses, *and* saves a record — which may itself be an SRP violation (Ch. 10). At minimum the name should reflect the domain: `RecordFileImporter`, `RecordLoader`, or similar.

---

**6. `processFile` mixes abstraction levels — G6, G34**

The method switches between high-level orchestration (`parseRecord`, `saveRecord`) and low-level file-system predicates (`f.exists()`, `f.canRead()`). These exist at different levels of abstraction. The file validation checks should be extracted into a named helper:

```java
// Extract low-level checks
private void validateReadable(File file) throws FileNotFoundException, FilePermissionException {
    if (!file.exists()) throw new FileNotFoundException(file.getPath());
    if (!file.canRead()) throw new FilePermissionException(file.getPath());
}
```

This also makes `processFile` read as a single-level narrative: validate → read → parse → save.

---

**7. `saveRecord` return value ignored implicitly — G2, Ch. 7**

```java
int result = saveRecord(record);
if (result != SUCCESS) return result;
```

`saveRecord` returns an `int` error code, which means it has the same design problem as `processFile`. If `saveRecord` is refactored to throw exceptions (as recommended above), this propagation pattern disappears. Flag this as part of the same systemic fix.

---

### 🟢 Suggestion

**8. Use `Files.readString` instead of `new String(Files.readAllBytes(...))` — G24**

`Files.readString(path)` (Java 11+) is the idiomatic replacement. It also accepts a `Charset` argument explicitly, avoiding the implicit default-charset dependency hidden in `new String(bytes)`. Follow Standard Conventions (G24).

---

**9. Class name `Record` is ambiguous since Java 16 — N1**

Java 16 introduced `record` as a keyword and `java.lang.Record` as a base class. A domain class named `Record` will create confusion. Rename to the actual domain concept: `CustomerRecord`, `TransactionRecord`, etc.

---

## Refactored Example

The most impactful section is `processFile` with its supporting infrastructure. Here is a rewrite of the class showing the exception-based approach:

```java
public class RecordFileImporter {

    /**
     * Loads, parses, and saves a record from the given file path.
     *
     * @throws FileNotFoundException   if the file does not exist
     * @throws FilePermissionException if the file cannot be read
     * @throws FileFormatException     if the content cannot be parsed
     * @throws RecordSaveException     if persistence fails
     */
    public void importRecord(String path)
            throws FileNotFoundException, FilePermissionException,
                   FileFormatException, RecordSaveException {

        File file = new File(path);         // renamed from 'f' — N1
        validateReadable(file);             // extracted — G34, G6

        String content = readFile(file);    // throws on failure, no null — Ch. 7
        Record record = parseRecord(content); // throws on failure, no null — Ch. 7

        saveRecord(record);                 // throws on failure — Ch. 7
    }

    // Extracted to keep processFile at one level of abstraction — G34
    private void validateReadable(File file)
            throws FileNotFoundException, FilePermissionException {
        if (!file.exists()) {
            throw new FileNotFoundException("File not found: " + file.getPath());
        }
        if (!file.canRead()) {
            throw new FilePermissionException("Cannot read file: " + file.getPath());
        }
    }

    // Propagates IOException with context instead of returning null — Ch. 7, G4
    private String readFile(File file) throws FileFormatException {
        try {
            return Files.readString(file.toPath());  // idiomatic Java 11+ — G24
        } catch (IOException e) {
            throw new FileFormatException("Failed to read file: " + file.getPath(), e);
        }
    }
}
```

Key changes and why:
- **No `int` return codes.** Each failure mode becomes a named, typed exception. Callers get structured information and the type system enforces handling. (Ch. 7, J3)
- **Dead null-check removed.** `new File(path)` never returns null. (G9)
- **`f` → `file`.** Intent-revealing at the scope it lives in. (N1, N5)
- **`validateReadable` extracted.** Keeps `importRecord` at one abstraction level. (G34)
- **`readFile` throws instead of returning null.** Exception carries the cause; nothing is swallowed. (Ch. 7, G4)
- **`Files.readString` used.** Standard idiom; explicit charset handling. (G24)
- **Class name updated.** `RecordFileImporter` describes one clear responsibility without using the vague `Processor` noun. (N1, SRP)

---

## Summary Table

| # | Issue | Severity | Heuristic |
|---|-------|----------|-----------|
| 1 | Error codes instead of exceptions | 🔴 Critical | Ch. 7, J3 |
| 2 | `readFile` swallows exceptions and returns null | 🔴 Critical | Ch. 7, G4 |
| 3 | Null check on `new File()` is unreachable dead code | 🔴 Critical | G9 |
| 4 | Single-letter variable `f` | 🟡 Improvement | N1, N5 |
| 5 | Vague class name `FileProcessor` | 🟡 Improvement | N1, N4 |
| 6 | `processFile` mixes abstraction levels | 🟡 Improvement | G6, G34 |
| 7 | `saveRecord` returns error code (systemic) | 🟡 Improvement | Ch. 7 |
| 8 | Use `Files.readString` (Java 11+) | 🟢 Suggestion | G24 |
| 9 | `Record` conflicts with Java 16 keyword | 🟢 Suggestion | N1 |

# Code Review: FileProcessor.java

## Summary

The `FileProcessor` class attempts to process a file by reading it, parsing a record, and saving that record. The overall structure is readable, but there are several issues — a redundant null check, silent exception swallowing, and the use of integer error codes instead of idiomatic Java error handling.

---

## Issues Found

### 1. Redundant null check on `new File(path)`

```java
File f = new File(path);
if (f == null) return ERR_FILE_NOT_FOUND;
```

`new File(path)` never returns `null` — it either returns a `File` instance or throws a `NullPointerException` if `path` is `null`. The `if (f == null)` check is dead code and will never be true. It creates a false sense of safety and misleads readers about what the method actually protects against.

**Fix:** Remove the dead null check. If a null `path` argument is a valid concern, validate it explicitly at the top and throw an `IllegalArgumentException` or handle it with a dedicated error code.

---

### 2. Silent exception swallowing in `readFile`

```java
private String readFile(File f) {
    try {
        return new String(Files.readAllBytes(f.toPath()));
    } catch (Exception e) {
        return null;
    }
}
```

Catching `Exception` broadly and returning `null` hides all failure information. The caller cannot distinguish between an `IOException` (e.g., disk error), a `SecurityException`, an `OutOfMemoryError` promoted to `Exception`, or any other throwable. The specific cause of the failure is permanently lost.

**Fix:** Either propagate the checked exception (declare `throws IOException`) or wrap it in a custom exception type that preserves the original cause. At minimum, log the exception before returning `null`.

---

### 3. Integer error codes instead of exceptions

```java
public static final int ERR_FILE_NOT_FOUND = -1;
public static final int ERR_PERMISSION = -2;
public static final int ERR_FORMAT = -3;
public static final int SUCCESS = 0;

public int processFile(String path) { ... }
```

Using integer return codes for error signaling is a C idiom. In Java, it forces every call site to check the return value, and callers can (and often do) ignore it silently. It also conflates "result of computation" with "error status," which makes the method's contract harder to understand and harder to extend.

**Fix:** Use exceptions. Checked exceptions (`IOException`, a custom `FileFormatException`) make errors part of the method contract and force callers to handle them. For truly unrecoverable or programming errors, use unchecked exceptions.

Example refactor:

```java
public void processFile(String path) throws IOException, FileFormatException {
    File f = new File(path);
    if (!f.exists()) throw new FileNotFoundException("File not found: " + path);
    if (!f.canRead()) throw new IOException("Cannot read file: " + path);

    String content = readFile(f);          // throws IOException on failure
    Record record = parseRecord(content);  // throws FileFormatException on bad format
    saveRecord(record);
}
```

---

### 4. No null check on `path` parameter

If `path` is `null`, `new File(null)` throws a `NullPointerException`, which will propagate up uncaught. The method gives no indication it expects a non-null argument.

**Fix:** Add an explicit precondition check at the entry point:

```java
if (path == null) throw new IllegalArgumentException("path must not be null");
```

Or, if staying with the return-code approach: `if (path == null) return ERR_FILE_NOT_FOUND;`

---

### 5. `readFile` uses default charset implicitly

```java
return new String(Files.readAllBytes(f.toPath()));
```

`new String(byte[])` uses the platform's default charset, which varies by OS and JVM configuration. This can cause silent data corruption or garbled text when moving between environments.

**Fix:** Specify the charset explicitly:

```java
return new String(Files.readAllBytes(f.toPath()), StandardCharsets.UTF_8);
```

Or use the simpler `Files.readString(f.toPath(), StandardCharsets.UTF_8)` (Java 11+).

---

### 6. Minor: Variable name `f` is too short

```java
File f = new File(path);
```

Single-letter variable names obscure intent. `file` is a clear, conventional name here.

---

## Summary Table

| # | Severity | Issue |
|---|----------|-------|
| 1 | Medium | Dead null check on `new File()` — misleading |
| 2 | High | Silent exception swallowing in `readFile` — hides root cause |
| 3 | High | Integer error codes instead of exceptions — un-idiomatic Java |
| 4 | Medium | No null guard on `path` parameter |
| 5 | Medium | Default charset used implicitly — not portable |
| 6 | Low | Variable `f` should be renamed to `file` |

---

## Recommended Refactor (Sketch)

```java
public class FileProcessor {

    public void processFile(String path) throws IOException, FileFormatException {
        if (path == null) throw new IllegalArgumentException("path must not be null");

        File file = new File(path);
        if (!file.exists()) throw new FileNotFoundException("File not found: " + path);
        if (!file.canRead()) throw new IOException("Permission denied: " + path);

        String content = readFile(file);
        Record record = parseRecord(content);
        saveRecord(record);
    }

    private String readFile(File file) throws IOException {
        return Files.readString(file.toPath(), StandardCharsets.UTF_8);
    }
}
```

This version uses exceptions for errors, removes dead code, preserves failure context, and specifies charset explicitly.

# Clean Code Review: `DataProcessor`

## Quick Summary

`DataProcessor` is a Java class with two methods: one that filters a list by a magic-number status flag, and one that conditionally persists, notifies, and logs a data record. Both methods suffer from opaque naming throughout, and `processData` compounds that with deeply nested conditionals and a five-argument signature that violates several core Clean Code principles. The code communicates almost nothing about its domain.

---

## What's Good

- The class is compact and scoped to a single concern at a high level — it is not trying to be a 500-line god class.
- `processData` does use a null-and-empty guard before acting on the string, which shows defensive thinking about preconditions.
- No commented-out code, no journal comments, no noise comments — the comment slate is clean.

---

## Issues

### 🔴 Critical

**1. Intention-hiding names throughout `getThem()` — N1, G16, G20**

Every identifier in `getThem()` obscures intent. `theList` tells us nothing about what is stored. `getThem` says nothing about what is being retrieved or why. `x` is a single-letter throwaway. `x[0] == 4` is a raw magic number with no meaning. A reader must hold contextual knowledge outside the code to understand a four-line method — that is the definition of opaque code (N1).

The magic number `4` is especially dangerous: it encodes a status value (likely something like `STATUS_FLAGGED` or `CELL_STATUS_INDEX`) with no documentation, making it a silent maintenance hazard (G25, G16).

**2. `processData` has five arguments — F1**

```java
public void processData(String d, int t, boolean f, String n, int r)
```

Five parameters is well past the triadic threshold. Each parameter is also single-letter, meaning the method signature provides zero information to the caller without reading the implementation. Clean Code is explicit: more than three arguments needs strong justification; beyond three, extract an argument object (F1).

**3. Flag argument `boolean f` — F3**

The boolean `f` is a classic flag argument. It loudly declares that `processData` does (at least) two things depending on whether `f` is true or false. The method should be split: one path for when the flag is true, one for when it is false — or, if the false-path currently does nothing, the boolean should be replaced by a predicate checked by the caller before invoking the method. Flag arguments are one of the most reliable signals that a function is doing more than one thing (F3, G30).

**4. `processData` does more than one thing — G30, G6**

Even ignoring the flag argument, the body of `processData` mixes at least four distinct operations at different levels of abstraction: printing output, persisting to a database, sending an email, and logging. A single function should do one thing. These are four separate concerns bundled together with no extractable naming to explain the composite intent (G30, G6).

**5. Arrow-shaped / deeply nested conditionals — G28**

```java
if (d != null && !d.isEmpty()) {
    if (t > 0) {
        if (f) {
            // actual work
        }
    }
}
```

Three levels of nested conditionals before any work is done. Clean Code advocates for guard clauses (early returns) to invert and flatten this structure. Deep nesting makes it hard to reason about preconditions and is a symptom of the function doing too much at too many levels (G28, G34).

---

### 🟡 Improvement

**6. Single-letter parameter names with no scope justification — N1, N5**

`d`, `t`, `f`, `n`, `r` are single-letter names in a method-level scope. N5 is explicit: single-letter names are acceptable only in very tight loop scopes (e.g., `i` in a 5-line loop). At method-parameter scope they are unacceptable — the reader cannot figure out what `t` or `r` represent without reading the body and reverse-engineering the call to `saveToDb` (N1, N5).

**7. Magic number `4` and magic array index `x[0]` — G25, G16**

`x[0]` accesses an unnamed field of an unnamed raw array. The fact that the data is stored as `int[]` rather than a typed object means the entire positional convention is implicit and fragile. `x[0] == 4` should be replaced with a named constant at minimum; ideally the data structure should be a proper domain object (G25, G16).

**8. Class name `DataProcessor` is a vague noun — N1**

`DataProcessor` uses the word "Processor" — explicitly called out in Clean Code as a vague, over-used class name that tells you nothing. What data? What kind of processing? The name should reflect the actual domain concept: `GameBoard`, `CellFilter`, `RecordSubmissionService`, or whatever the actual domain is (N1).

**9. `theList` as a field name — N1, G16**

The `the` prefix is pure noise. `theList` is equivalent to `list`, which is itself meaningless. The field name should describe what the list contains: `cells`, `gameBoard`, `pendingRecords`, etc. (N1).

---

### 🟢 Suggestion

**10. Raw `int[]` should be a domain object — Ch. 6**

Storing domain data as `int[]` is a primitive obsession smell. Even a simple record class or DTO would give names to the fields and make `x[0] == 4` readable as `cell.getStatus() == CellStatus.FLAGGED`. This also eliminates the fragile positional-index dependency.

**11. `System.out.println` is a side effect inconsistent with the method's apparent purpose — N7**

Direct console output inside a data-processing method is a hidden side effect. If logging/output is needed, it belongs in a proper logger (e.g., `java.util.logging` or SLF4J) at the call site or in a dedicated logging layer — not embedded in a business method (N7).

---

## Refactored Example

The most impactful section to rewrite is the pair of methods together, as the naming problems in `getThem` and the structural problems in `processData` are tightly related.

```java
// BEFORE
public class DataProcessor {
    private List<int[]> theList = new ArrayList<>();

    public List<int[]> getThem() {
        List<int[]> list1 = new ArrayList<>();
        for (int[] x : theList)
            if (x[0] == 4)
                list1.add(x);
        return list1;
    }

    public void processData(String d, int t, boolean f, String n, int r) {
        if (d != null && !d.isEmpty()) {
            if (t > 0) {
                if (f) {
                    System.out.println(d);
                    saveToDb(d, t, n);
                    sendEmail(n, d);
                    logResult(d, r);
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

```java
// AFTER — assuming a Minesweeper-like domain where cells have statuses
// and records are submitted with a timeout, active flag, and result code

public class GameBoard {                                  // N1: descriptive class name

    private static final int STATUS_FLAGGED = 4;         // G25: named constant replaces magic 4

    private List<Cell> cells = new ArrayList<>();        // N1: field name describes contents

    public List<Cell> getFlaggedCells() {                // G20, N1: name says exactly what is returned
        List<Cell> flaggedCells = new ArrayList<>();
        for (Cell cell : cells)
            if (cell.isFlagged())                        // G28: encapsulated conditional on domain object
                flaggedCells.add(cell);
        return flaggedCells;
    }
